# Catalyst One — Enterprise UX Standard

Applies to **all present and future screens**.

Optimise for **user workflow**, information visibility, and operational efficiency — not decorative component placement.

## Screen layout

- Design responsively; use available space efficiently.
- Avoid unnecessary vertical stacking.
- Keep the most important operational information visible without excessive scrolling.

## Responsive behaviour

Layouts must adapt to laptop, desktop, and large monitors.

Avoid fixed heights whenever possible. Prefer fluid/`min`/`max` constraints over locked viewport traps.

## Data tables

Important operational tables should remain visible within the primary viewport whenever practical.

Do **not** push tables below multiple large widgets. If vertical space is constrained, **reorganize the layout** rather than hiding critical data.

## Filters

Use compact enterprise filter chips. Avoid oversized buttons. Reduce padding while maintaining readability.

## Visual balance

Charts, cards, tables, and filters must appear visually balanced. No single element should dominate the page unnecessarily.

## CHANAKYA Radar (when touching Radar)

- Allow the radar component to **resize dynamically**.
- Quadrant labels must remain **outside** the radar.
- Labels must never overlap or touch the visualization.

## Scrolling

Every page must remain scrollable when content exceeds the viewport.

Never create layouts where content becomes inaccessible (clipped, overflow-hidden traps without an alternate scroll path).

## Completion checklist

Before considering any screen complete, validate:

- No clipped content
- No inaccessible tables
- No overlapping labels
- Balanced spacing
- Responsive layout
- Comfortable reading

## Relationship to other rules

- Complements `enterprise-workspace-ux.mdc` (workspace chrome, Close, document scroll).
- Complements `enterprise-accessibility-contrast.mdc` (contrast).
- When both apply, satisfy workspace chrome **and** this screen-layout standard.
